---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GeneratorShell from '../../components/GeneratorShell.astro';

const title = 'Random SQL SELECT Query Generator | Genfy';
const description = 'Generate random SELECT queries with joins, where, group by and order by. Useful for SQL practice and documentation samples.';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is this generator for?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For practicing SQL, building documentation samples or having a base query you tweak manually.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which dialect?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The queries use ANSI standard SQL, compatible with PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite and SQL Server with minimal adjustments.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Why use explicit JOIN?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Explicit JOINs are more readable, separate filter conditions from join conditions and prevent accidental cartesian products.' } },
  ],
};
---
<Layout title={title} description={description} lang="en" schema={faqSchema} withSidebar={true}>
  <GeneratorShell
    lang="en"
    tag="Tech / Dev"
    title="Random SQL SELECT Query"
    intro="Generate SELECT queries with JOIN, WHERE, GROUP BY and ORDER BY for practice or documentation."
  >
    <div slot="tool" class="sql-tool">
      <div class="sql-grid">
        <div>
          <label for="sql-complexity">Complexity</label>
          <select id="sql-complexity">
            <option value="simple">Simple</option>
            <option value="join">With JOIN</option>
            <option value="agg">Aggregated (GROUP BY)</option>
            <option value="window">Window function</option>
            <option value="cte">With CTE</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="sql-domain">Domain</label>
          <select id="sql-domain">
            <option value="ecommerce">E-commerce</option>
            <option value="hr">HR</option>
            <option value="blog">Blog</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sql-actions">
        <button id="sql-gen" class="btn btn-primary" type="button">Generate</button>
        <button id="sql-copy" class="btn btn-ghost" type="button"><span class="copy-icon">Copy</span></button>
      </div>
      <textarea id="sql-out" class="mono" rows="12" readonly></textarea>
    </div>

    <div slot="content">
      <h2>SELECT structure</h2>
      <p>
        The logical evaluation order is: FROM &rarr; JOIN &rarr; WHERE &rarr; GROUP BY &rarr;
        HAVING &rarr; SELECT &rarr; ORDER BY &rarr; LIMIT. Counterintuitive: although you write
        SELECT first, it runs near the end. That's why you can't use a SELECT alias inside the
        WHERE of the same query.
      </p>

      <h2>Explicit vs implicit JOINs</h2>
      <p>
        It used to be common to write <code>FROM a, b WHERE a.id = b.a_id</code>. Today the
        correct form is <code>FROM a JOIN b ON a.id = b.a_id</code>. Explicit syntax separates
        join conditions from filters, prevents accidental cartesian products and makes the join
        type clear (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL).
      </p>

      <h2>WHERE vs HAVING</h2>
      <p>
        WHERE filters rows before aggregation; HAVING filters groups after. If you don't use
        GROUP BY, use WHERE. <code>HAVING COUNT(*) &gt; 10</code> makes sense; <code>HAVING age
        &gt; 18</code> without GROUP BY is likely a bug.
      </p>

      <h2>Subqueries vs JOINs vs CTEs</h2>
      <p>
        For data you'll use multiple times, a CTE (<code>WITH x AS (SELECT ...)</code>) is more
        readable than repeating a subquery. Modern planners typically optimize them like inline
        subqueries. For simple cases, a JOIN is usually faster and clearer than a subquery.
      </p>

      <h2>Window functions</h2>
      <p>
        ROW_NUMBER, RANK, DENSE_RANK, LAG, LEAD and aggregations with OVER allow per-partition
        calculations without collapsing rows. For "top 3 products per category", use
        <code>ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY category ORDER BY sales DESC)</code> and filter
        where row_number &le; 3 (in a CTE).
      </p>

      <h2>Performance: indexes and EXPLAIN</h2>
      <p>
        Before optimizing, run <code>EXPLAIN ANALYZE</code> (Postgres) or <code>EXPLAIN</code>
        (MySQL). Look for sequential scans on large tables, sorts without index and nested loops
        with many iterations. Rule of thumb: index columns used in JOIN and WHERE; on queries
        with ORDER BY + LIMIT, an index on the order column helps.
      </p>

      <h2>SELECT * is an anti-pattern</h2>
      <p>
        It pulls all columns, transfers bytes you don't use, prevents covering indexes and breaks
        if someone adds a sensitive column. List the columns you need explicitly. Genfy generates
        explicit SELECT in every example.
      </p>

      <h2>SQL injection</h2>
      <p>
        Never concatenate user input into the query. Use parameters (<code>$1, $2</code> in
        Postgres, <code>?</code> in MySQL) or an ORM that handles them. The queries here are
        examples for understanding; in production use prepared statements.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div slot="faq">
      <details><summary>What is it for?</summary><p>Practice SQL, build documentation samples or get base queries.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Which dialect?</summary><p>ANSI standard SQL, compatible with most relational databases.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Why explicit JOIN?</summary><p>More readable, separates joins from filters, prevents cartesian products.</p></details>
    </div>
  </GeneratorShell>
</Layout>

<style>
  .sql-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  @media (max-width: 600px) { .sql-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
  .sql-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  textarea { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.875rem; background: var(--bg-inset); resize: vertical; width: 100%; }
</style>

<script>
  const cx = document.getElementById('sql-complexity') as HTMLSelectElement;
  const dom = document.getElementById('sql-domain') as HTMLSelectElement;
  const out = document.getElementById('sql-out') as HTMLTextAreaElement;
  const gen = document.getElementById('sql-gen') as HTMLButtonElement;
  const copy = document.getElementById('sql-copy') as HTMLButtonElement;

  type Q = { simple: string; join: string; agg: string; window: string; cte: string };
  const queries: Record<string, Q> = {
    ecommerce: {
      simple: `SELECT id, sku, name, price, stock
FROM products
WHERE stock > 0
  AND price BETWEEN 10 AND 500
ORDER BY price DESC
LIMIT 50;`,
      join: `SELECT o.id, o.created_at, c.name AS customer, p.name AS product, oi.quantity, oi.price
FROM orders o
INNER JOIN customers c ON c.id = o.customer_id
INNER JOIN order_items oi ON oi.order_id = o.id
INNER JOIN products p ON p.id = oi.product_id
WHERE o.status = 'paid'
  AND o.created_at >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '30 days'
ORDER BY o.created_at DESC;`,
      agg: `SELECT c.id, c.name, COUNT(o.id) AS orders_count, SUM(o.total) AS total_spent
FROM customers c
LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.customer_id = c.id AND o.status = 'paid'
GROUP BY c.id, c.name
HAVING COUNT(o.id) > 0
ORDER BY total_spent DESC
LIMIT 20;`,
      window: `SELECT category, name, sales,
       ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY category ORDER BY sales DESC) AS rn,
       SUM(sales) OVER (PARTITION BY category) AS category_total
FROM (
  SELECT p.category, p.name, SUM(oi.quantity * oi.price) AS sales
  FROM products p
  JOIN order_items oi ON oi.product_id = p.id
  GROUP BY p.category, p.name
) t
ORDER BY category, rn;`,
      cte: `WITH monthly_sales AS (
  SELECT DATE_TRUNC('month', o.created_at) AS month,
         SUM(o.total) AS revenue
  FROM orders o
  WHERE o.status = 'paid'
  GROUP BY 1
),
ranked AS (
  SELECT month, revenue,
         LAG(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY month) AS prev_revenue
  FROM monthly_sales
)
SELECT month, revenue, prev_revenue,
       ROUND(100.0 * (revenue - prev_revenue) / prev_revenue, 2) AS growth_pct
FROM ranked
ORDER BY month;`,
    },
    hr: {
      simple: `SELECT id, full_name, department, salary
FROM employees
WHERE active = true
ORDER BY salary DESC
LIMIT 25;`,
      join: `SELECT e.id, e.full_name, d.name AS department, p.title AS position
FROM employees e
INNER JOIN departments d ON d.id = e.department_id
INNER JOIN positions p ON p.id = e.position_id
WHERE e.active = true
ORDER BY d.name, e.full_name;`,
      agg: `SELECT d.name AS department, COUNT(*) AS headcount, AVG(e.salary) AS avg_salary
FROM employees e
INNER JOIN departments d ON d.id = e.department_id
WHERE e.active = true
GROUP BY d.name
ORDER BY headcount DESC;`,
      window: `SELECT full_name, department_id, salary,
       RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY department_id ORDER BY salary DESC) AS dept_rank,
       AVG(salary) OVER (PARTITION BY department_id) AS dept_avg
FROM employees
WHERE active = true
ORDER BY department_id, dept_rank;`,
      cte: `WITH dept_avg AS (
  SELECT department_id, AVG(salary) AS avg_salary
  FROM employees
  WHERE active = true
  GROUP BY department_id
)
SELECT e.full_name, e.salary, d.avg_salary,
       ROUND(e.salary - d.avg_salary, 2) AS diff_from_avg
FROM employees e
JOIN dept_avg d ON d.department_id = e.department_id
WHERE e.active = true
ORDER BY diff_from_avg DESC;`,
    },
    blog: {
      simple: `SELECT id, slug, title, published_at
FROM posts
WHERE published = true
ORDER BY published_at DESC
LIMIT 10;`,
      join: `SELECT p.id, p.title, u.name AS author, COUNT(c.id) AS comments_count
FROM posts p
INNER JOIN users u ON u.id = p.author_id
LEFT JOIN comments c ON c.post_id = p.id
WHERE p.published = true
GROUP BY p.id, p.title, u.name
ORDER BY p.published_at DESC
LIMIT 20;`,
      agg: `SELECT u.id, u.name, COUNT(p.id) AS posts_count, MAX(p.published_at) AS last_post
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN posts p ON p.author_id = u.id AND p.published = true
GROUP BY u.id, u.name
HAVING COUNT(p.id) > 5
ORDER BY posts_count DESC;`,
      window: `SELECT title, published_at,
       LAG(title) OVER (ORDER BY published_at) AS previous_post,
       LEAD(title) OVER (ORDER BY published_at) AS next_post
FROM posts
WHERE published = true
ORDER BY published_at DESC
LIMIT 50;`,
      cte: `WITH tag_stats AS (
  SELECT t.name, COUNT(pt.post_id) AS post_count
  FROM tags t
  JOIN post_tags pt ON pt.tag_id = t.id
  GROUP BY t.name
)
SELECT name, post_count
FROM tag_stats
WHERE post_count >= 3
ORDER BY post_count DESC
LIMIT 25;`,
    },
  };

  function build() {
    const q = queries[dom.value][cx.value as keyof Q];
    out.value = q;
  }
  gen.addEventListener('click', build);
  [cx, dom].forEach(el => el.addEventListener('change', build));
  copy.addEventListener('click', async () => {
    if (!out.value) return;
    await navigator.clipboard.writeText(out.value);
    const icon = copy.querySelector('.copy-icon') as HTMLElement;
    icon.textContent = '✓ Copied';
    setTimeout(() => { icon.textContent = 'Copy'; }, 1400);
  });
  build();
</script>
</content>
</invoke>